 critiques the psychological conjecture that Alfred’s childhood memory was their common source, and shows that synoptically they can help us see how Alfred shaped the curve of his own life’s destiny and how he engaged in the formation of his own cult to last a thousand years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHagiography. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aMedieval Studies. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh  aAlfred the Great, autohagiography, childhood memory, historicity, medieval biliteracy.1 aPrescott, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048544998?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048544998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048544998/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK